## Working with Images

The Framer developer platform provides a collection of top-level functions for adding and manipulating images.

### Adding Images to the Canvas

Images can be added to the canvas using the `addImage` method. This method supports various sources:

*   **From a URL:** Provide the image URL, a name, and optional alt text.

    ```
    await framer.addImage({
      image: "https://example.com/image.png",
      name: 'My image',
      altText: "Alt description"
    })
    ```

*   **From a File Input:** Obtain a `File` object from a file input element and pass it to `addImage`.

    ```
    const fileInput = document.querySelector(`input[type="file"]`)
    const file = fileInput.files[0]

    const image = await framer.addImage({
      image: file,
      name: "Uploaded image",
      altText: "Alt Description"
    })
    ```

*   **Shorthand for File Input:** A simpler syntax exists for adding a file.

    ```
    const image = await framer.addImage(file)
    ```

### Setting an Image on the Selected Node

The `setImage` method allows applying an image to the currently selected node on the canvas. This works if the node supports image settings or if it's a Component Node with a single Image control prop.

```
await framer.setImage({ image: "https://example.com/image.png", altText: "Alt Description" })
```

### Image Resolution

All image-related methods (`addImage`, `setImage`) allow specifying the image resolution. The available options are `"auto"` (default), `"lossless"`, `"small"`, `"medium"`, `"large"`, or `"full"`. These correspond to the options available in the Framer UI.

```
await framer.addImage({ image: "https://example.com/image.png", resolution: "lossless" })
```

### Uploading Images Without Assigning Them to a Node

It's possible to upload images to Framer's asset management system without immediately placing them on the canvas. The `uploadImage` method handles this, returning an `ImageAsset` object that can be used later.

```
const image = await framer.uploadImage({
  image: 'https://example.com/image.png',
  name: 'My image',
  altText: "alt Description"
})

// Later, use the image for creating a node
await framer.createFrameNode({
  backgroundImage: image
})
```

### Getting an Image from Selection

To retrieve the image of the current selection, if one exists, the `getImage()` function can be used.

```
const image = await framer.getImage()
```

To react to changes in the selected image, the `subscribeToImage` listener is available. A common pattern is to abstract this into a React hook:

```
import { framer, ImageAsset } from 'framer-plugin'

function useImageSelection() {
    const [image, setImage] = useState<ImageAsset | null>(null)
    useEffect(() => {
        return framer.subscribeToImage(setImage)
    }, [])
    return image
}
```

### Modifying the Alt Text of an Image

To update only the `altText` of an image without changing the image content itself, you can iterate through image nodes, clone their `backgroundImage` attribute with updated alt text, and then set the new attributes.

```
const imageNodes = await framer.getNodesWithAttributeSet("backgroundImage")
for (const imageNode of imageNodes) {
    if (!imageNode.backgroundImage) continue

    await imageNode.setAttributes({
        backgroundImage: imageNode.backgroundImage.cloneWithAttributes({
          altText: "Updated Alt Text"
        }),
    })
}
```

### Example: Image Processing

For plugins that manipulate images, Framer provides raw image bytes and utilities. A convenient way to perform image manipulation is by rendering the image bitmap on an HTML canvas. The `loadBitmap()` method of an `ImageAsset` converts the image into an `ImageBitmap` supported by canvas.

```
// Get the selected image in framer
const image = await framer.getImage()

const canvas = document.createElement("canvas")
const ctx = canvas.getContext("2d")

// Load the image bytes into an ImageBitmap that canvas supports
const bitmap = await image.loadBitmap()

// Set the height of the canvas to the height of the image
ctx.canvas.width = img.width;
ctx.canvas.height = img.height;

// Here we horizontally invert the image bitmap.
ctx.scale(-1, 1);
ctx.drawImage(bitmap, -bitmap.width, 0);

const result = await bytesFromCanvas(canvas);

await framer.addImage({
  image: { bytes: result, mimeType },
});
```

## Working with Files

Code components can be configured to accept files by adding `ControlType.File` to their property controls. Plugins can upload files to Framer and assign them to these component controls.

The `uploadFile` method is used for this purpose, accepting either a URL or a `File` object.

```
const uploadedFile = await framer.uploadFile({
  // You can also pass "File" objects
  // To accept <input type="file" /> inputs.
  file: "https://example.com/video.mp4",
  name: "Example Video"
})

// Insert a Video Component with the uploaded file
await framer.addComponentInstance({
  url: "https://framer.com/m/framer/Video.js#Video",
  attributes: {
    controls: {
      srcType: "Upload",
      srcFile: uploadedFile,
    },
  },
})
```

## Working with SVGs

### Adding Small SVGs

For SVGs smaller than 10kb, the `addSVG` asynchronous function can be used. It takes the SVG HTML string and a name.

```
await framer.addSVG({
  svg: `<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20"><path d="M5 2.5h10v5h-5Zm0 5h5l5 5H5Zm5 5v5l-5-5Z"/></svg>`,
  name: "framer.svg",
})
```

### Adding Larger SVGs as Bytes

If an SVG exceeds 10kb, it should be passed as byte data using the `addImage` function, specifying the `mimeType` as `"image/svg+xml"`.

```
await framer.addImage({
  image: {
    type: "bytes",
    bytes: new TextEncoder().encode(svgInput),
    mimeType: "image/svg+xml",
  },
  name: "SVG",
});
```

## Working with Nodes in Framer

Nodes are the fundamental building blocks that comprise content within a Framer project. In the editor user interface, these nodes are visually represented as "layers."

### Node Types

Framer defines several distinct types of nodes, each equipped with its own specific properties and methods. The key node types include:

*   `FrameNode`: Represents a frame on the canvas.
*   `TextNode`: Represents text content.
*   `SVGNode`: Represents Scalable Vector Graphics.
*   `CodeComponentNode`: Represents a custom code component.
*   `UnknownNode`: A generic node type for items not explicitly categorized.

### Getting Nodes

Developers often need to retrieve nodes, typically based on user selections or specific criteria. Framer provides several APIs for this:

*   **Getting Selected Nodes:** Most frequently, plugins interact with nodes currently selected on the canvas. The `framer.getSelection()` asynchronous function returns an array of the currently selected nodes.
    ```
    const selection = await framer.getSelection()
    ```

*   **Subscribing to Selection Changes:** To react to changes in the user's selection, developers can subscribe to selection events. The `framer.subscribeToSelection(setSelection)` function allows a callback to be notified when the selection changes.
    ```
    function useSelection() {
      const [selection, setSelection] = useState<CanvasNode[]>([])

      useEffect(() => {
        return framer.subscribeToSelection(setSelection)
      }, [])

      return selection
    }
    ```

*   **Getting a Node by ID:** If the unique ID of a node is known, it can be retrieved directly using `framer.getNode("some-node-id")`.
    ```
    const node = await framer.getNode("some-node-id")
    ```

*   **Getting Nodes by Criteria:** For broader queries, the `getNodesWith…()` family of APIs allows retrieval of nodes that match specific criteria across the entire project. This includes options to filter by node type or attributes.

    *   **By Node Type:** `framer.getNodesWithType("FrameNode")` can fetch all nodes of a particular type, e.g., all `FrameNode` instances.
        ```
        // Get all frame nodes in a project.
        const frameNodes = await framer.getNodesWithType("FrameNode")
        ```

    *   **By Attribute:** `framer.getNodesWithAttribute("backgroundColor")` can retrieve nodes that possess a specific attribute, regardless of their primary type.
        ```
        // Get any kind of node that has a background color set.
        const nodes = await framer.getNodesWithAttribute("backgroundColor")
        ```

    *   **Querying within a Selection:** These APIs can also be scoped to operate only within a currently selected node or its subtree. For example, `selectedNode.getNodesWithType("FrameNode")` or `selectedNode.getNodesWithAttribute("backgroundColor")`.
        ```
        const selection = await framer.getSelection()
        const selectedNode = selection.length === 1 ? selection[0] : null

        // To get all nodes of a certain sub tree
        if (selectedNode) {
          const frameNodes = await selectedNode.getNodesWithType("FrameNode")
          const nodes = await selectedNode.getNodesWithAttribute("backgroundColor")
          const nodes = await selectedNode.getNodesWithAttributeSet("backgroundColor")
        }
        ```

    *   **Example: `useAllBackgroundImages` Hook:** A practical use case demonstrates retrieving all background images set on `FrameNode`s within a project, showcasing the combination of `getNodesWithAttributeSet` and state management.
        ```
        function useAllBackgroundImages() {
          const [images, setImages] = useState<ImageAsset[]>([])

          useEffect(() => {
            let active = true

            async function run() {
              // Get all Nodes with a background image set
              const nodes = await framer.getNodesWithAttributeSet("backgroundImage")

              // Use a Map to remove duplicates
              const uniqueImages = new Map<string, ImageAsset>()

              for (const item of nodes) {
                const image = item.backgroundImage
                if (!image) continue

                uniqueImages.set(image.id, image)
              }

              if (!active) return
              setImages(Array.from(uniqueImages.values()))
            }

            run()

            return () => {
              active = false
            }
          }, [])

          return images
        }
        ```

### Creating Nodes

Nodes can also be programmatically created and added to the canvas:

*   **Creating a Generic Frame:** `framer.createFrameNode()` instantiates a basic frame on the canvas.
    ```
    framer.createFrameNode()
    ```

*   **Adding Text:** `framer.addText()` is used to place text content on the canvas.
    ```
    framer.addText()
    ```

More specialized methods exist for creating images, SVGs, and code components, detailed in their respective documentation sections.

### Traits for Node Differentiation and Manipulation

Traits serve as a mechanism to identify different kinds of nodes or nodes possessing specific attributes. They are crucial for conditional manipulation.

*   **Checking Node Types:** Trait functions prefixed with `is` (e.g., `isTextNode`, `isFrameNode`, `isSVGNode`, `isCodeComponentNode`) allow developers to ascertain a node's type. This is vital before attempting type-specific operations, such as setting text on a `TextNode`.
    ```
    const selection = await framer.getSelection()

    for (const node of selection) {
      // We need to check what the node is because 
      // the `setText` method is only available on 
      // text nodes.
      if (isTextNode(node)) {
        node.setText("Hello!")
      }
    }
    ```

*   **Checking Node Attributes:** Trait functions beginning with `supports` (e.g., `supportsPosition`, `supportsVisible`, `supportsRotation`, `supportsBackgroundGradient`, `supportsBorderRadius`) are used to determine if a node supports a particular attribute. This is useful as different node types might share common attributes.
    ```
    const selection = await framer.getSelection()

    for (const node of selection) {
      if (supportsBackroundImage(node)) {
        console.log(node)
      }
    }
    ```
    A comprehensive list of traits can be found in the `index.d.ts` types file.

### Replicas

Each node has an `isReplica` property that indicates if it is a replica. Replica nodes are used in non-primary breakpoints and component variants. They inherit attributes from their primary variant or breakpoint. When an attribute on a replica node is overridden, it ceases to inherit from the primary and is instead explicitly set on that replica.

### Children & Parents (Layer Hierarchy)

Nodes form a hierarchical structure. Developers can access a node's immediate parent or children using the `getParent()` and `getChildren()` asynchronous functions respectively. These are essential for navigating and manipulating the layer hierarchy.

### Working with Async Layer APIs

Combining asynchronous APIs for layers is a common pattern in Framer development. An example demonstrates retrieving children and bounding rectangles (`getRect()`) of a selected parent node using `Promise.all()` to efficiently fetch multiple pieces of data concurrently.

```
useEffect(() => {
  let active = true;

  async function run() {
    if (!active) return;

    const parentNode = selection[0];

    if (!parentNode || selection.length !== 1) {
      setState(null);
      return;
    }

    const layerPromises = [parentNode.getChildren(), parentNode.getRect()]
    const [children, parentRect] = await Promise.all(layerPromises)

    // Exit to not support no selection or multiselect
    if (children.length !== 1 || !parentRect) {
      setState(null);
      return;
    }

    const singleChild = children[0];
    const childRect = await singleChild.getRect()

    if (!childRect) {
      setState(null);
      return;
    }

    setState({
      parent: parentNode,
      child: singleChild,
      parentRect,
      childRect,
    });
  }

  run()

  // cleanup function
  return () => {
    active = false;
  };
}, selection)
```

