# Working with Styles

Styles in Framer allow developers to manage text and color appearances from a centralized location within a project, accessible via the Assets panel in the UI. Plugins can leverage these styles for various functionalities, such as syncing design systems or performing accessibility checks.

## Color Styles

Color styles encapsulate color definitions for use across a Framer project, supporting light and dark themes.

### Retrieving and Listing Color Styles

To retrieve all color styles in a project, use `framer.getColorStyles()`. To get a specific color style by its ID, use `framer.getColorStyle("color-style-id")`.

```
// Lists all Color Styles in a project.
const colorStyles = await framer.getColorStyles()

// Get a specfic Color Style by it's ID.
const colorStyle = await framer.getColorStyle("color-style-id")
```

### Creating Color Styles

When creating a new color style with `framer.createColorStyle()`, the `light` attribute defines the default color used in the light theme. The `dark` attribute is an optional color for the dark theme. Colors are specified in RGBA format (e.g., `rgba(242, 59, 57, 1)`).

```
const colorStyle = await framer.createColorStyle({
  name: "My Cool Color",
  light: "rgba(242, 59, 57, 1)",
  dark: "rgba(120, 22, 11, 1)"
})
```

Color styles can be organized into folders by using a forward slash (`/`) as a separator in the `name` attribute. For instance, `"My Plugin/My Cool Color"` will create a 'My Plugin' folder with the style inside.

```
const colorStyle = await framer.createColorStyle({
  name: "My Plugin/My Cool Color",
  // ...
})
```

### Updating Color Styles

Existing color styles can be updated using the `setAttributes()` method, similar to updating nodes. For example, to change the dark theme color:

```
await colorStyle.setAttributes({ dark: "rgba(10, 10, 10, 0.2)" })
```

### Removing Color Styles

To remove a color style, acquire a reference to the style object and call its `remove()` method.

```
await colorStyle.remove()
```

### Storing Plugin Data on Color Styles

Individual color styles can store plugin-specific data using `setPluginData("key", "value")`.

```
await colorStyle.setPluginData("key", "value")
```

## Text Styles

Text styles manage typographic properties, allowing for consistent text appearance throughout a project.

### Retrieving and Listing Text Styles

To retrieve all text styles in a project, use `framer.getTextStyles()`. To get a specific text style by its ID, use `framer.getTextStyle("text-style-id")`.

```
// Lists all Text Styles in a project.
const textStyle = await framer.getTextStyles()

// Get a specfic Text Style by it's ID.
const textStyle = await framer.getTextStyle("text-style-id")
```

### Creating Text Styles

New text styles can be added to the project using `framer.createTextStyle()`, defining properties like `name`, `tag` (e.g., "h1"), `fontSize`, and `lineHeight`.

```
const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  name: "Heading",
  tag: "h1",
  fontSize: "30px",
  lineHeight: "1.6em"
})
```

Similar to color styles, text styles can be organized into folders by using a forward slash (`/`) in the `name` attribute.

```
const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  name: "My Plugin/Heading",
  // ...
})
```

### Updating Text Styles

Existing text styles can be updated using `setAttributes()`. For instance, to change the color of a text style:

```
const textStyle = await framer.getTextStyle("text-style-id")
if (!textStyle) return

await textStyle.setAttributes({
  // Set the color of the Text Style to red.
  color: "rgba(242, 59, 57, 1)"
})
```

### Removing Text Styles

To remove a text style, acquire a reference to the style object and call its `remove()` method.

```
await textStyle.remove()
```

### Storing Plugin Data on Text Styles

Individual text styles can store plugin-specific data using `setPluginData("key", "value")`.

```
await textStyle.setPluginData("key", "value")
```

## Breakpoints for Text Styles

Text styles can include variations that apply at different window widths, defined as breakpoints. The main text style's attributes are considered the largest breakpoint.

When defining breakpoints, you can specify `minWidth` and the corresponding style attributes. For example, a text style could be `24px` at `1280px` and beyond, `18px` between `1024px` and `1280px`, and `16px` between `320px` and `1024px`.

```
const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  fontSize: "24px",
  minWidth: 1280,
  breakpoints: [
    { minWidth: 1024, fontSize: "18px" },
    { minWidth: 320, fontSize: "16px" }
  ]
})
```

*   A maximum of four breakpoints can be added, and an error will be thrown if this limit is exceeded.
*   Breakpoints are automatically ordered from largest to smallest, so their definition order does not matter.
*   Each breakpoint must have a unique `minWidth`; otherwise, an error will be thrown.

When updating a text style, setting the `breakpoints` attribute with `setAttributes()` will override any existing breakpoints on that text style. Other attributes will be combined with existing ones.

```
// Make a new Text Style with breakpoints.
const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  fontSize: "24px",
  minWidth: 1280,
  breakpoints: [
    { minWidth: 1024, fontSize: "18px" },
    { minWidth: 320, fontSize: "16px" }
  ]
})

// Update the created Text Style with new breakpoints.
await textStyle.setAttributes({
  // Only one breakpoint will now exist on the Text Style.
  breakpoints: [
    { minWidth: 320, fontSize: "24px" }
  ]
})
```

To update breakpoints without completely overriding them, one must iterate over the existing breakpoints and merge the desired changes. An example is provided for scaling font sizes across all text styles and their breakpoints.

```
const textStyles = await framer.getTextStyles()

for (const textStyle of textStyles) {
  await textStyle.set({
    fontSize: parseInt(breakpoint.fontSize) * 0.8 + "px",
    breakpoints: textStyle.breakpoints.map((breakpoint) => {
      return {
        ...breakpoint,
        fontSize: parseInt(breakpoint.fontSize) * 0.8 + "px"
      }
    })
  })
}
```

## Fonts for Text Styles

By default, text styles use a built-in font. To customize a text style's typeface, set the `font` attribute when creating or updating a style using `framer.getFont("Font Name")`.

```
const font = await framer.getFont("Open Sans")
if (!font) return

const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  font
})
```

Framer automatically assigns suitable fonts for bold, italic, and bold italic variants. These can be overridden for finer typographic control by providing `boldFont`, `italicFont`, and `boldItalicFont` attributes, specifying `weight` and `style`.

```
const font = await framer.getFont("Open Sans", { 
  weight: 100 
})

const boldFont = await framer.getFont("Open Sans", {
  weight: 400 
})

const italicFont = await framer.getFont("Open Sans", { 
  weight: 100, 
  style: "italic" 
})

const boldItalicFont = await framer.getFont("Open Sans", { 
  weight: 400,
  style: "italic"
})

if (!font || !boldFont || !italicFont || !boldItalicFont) return

const textStyle = await framer.createTextStyle({
  // Base.
  font,

  // Variants.
  boldFont,
  italicFont,
  boldItalicFont
})
```

All specified fonts must belong to the same family; using fonts from different families will result in an error. Font attributes, such as `font.family`, can be retrieved from a text style object, checking for existence before accessing variant fonts.

```
const textStyle = await framer.getTextStyle("text-style-id")

// Log out the family name for the base font.
console.log(textStyle.font.family)

// Font variants may not be defined, check that they exist
// before accessing them.
if (textStyle.boldFont) {
  console.log(textStyle.boldFont.family)
}
```

